{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"27d2e733-76e7-479d-ada9-571069d0b1a2","content":"## What's happening\n\nStarting with recent .NET versions, the runtime raised the **minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level** from **x86-64-v1** (original AMD64) to **x86-64-v2**. Your 2012-era hardware likely predates the required instruction sets.\n\n**x86-64-v2 requires:** SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B — instructions generally available from Intel Haswell (2013) / AMD Jaguar (2013) onward. Pre-2013 CPUs (Sandy Bridge, Bulldozer) may lack some of these.\n\n## Diagnosing\n\nOn the failing node, check what it supports:\n\n```bash\n# Show CPU flags\ngrep -oP '(sse3|ssse3|sse4_1|sse4_2|popcnt|cx16|avx|avx2)' /proc/cpuinfo | sort -u\n```\n\n## Your other platforms\n\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1):** Unaffected — Arm64 has its own baseline (NEON/AdvSIMD, always present).\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Linux Arm64):** Unaffected — same reason.\n- **Newer x86-64 Linux nodes:** Likely fine if the hardware is 2013+.\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Replace the old hardware** — cheapest long-term fix.\n2. **Pin that node to .NET 10** until it's retired.\n3. **Build a custom runtime** from source targeting x86-64-v1 (unsupported, not recommended for production).\n\nThe runtime made this change to unlock better default codegen (e.g., using SSE4.2 for string operations, POPCNT for `BitOperations`) without per-call feature checks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5d7de41d-5d20-4595-a2f0-92502f886688","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's evolving hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing to search code.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 10 (or potentially .NET 11 based on the timeline), Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT instructions. \n\nOlder hardware from around 2012 likely lacks support for these newer instruction sets, which explains why the error appears after the upgrade. .NET 10 introduced this baseline requirement for x86-64 Linux systems, making it a breaking change for machines with older processors. So if .NET 11 bumped the baseline to x86-64-v3, that would require Haswell or newer Intel chips and Zen-era AMD processors—meaning anything from 2012 like Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge would fall short since they lack AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, and FMA support. Let me check what's actually documented about the .NET version baselines to confirm this theory. The most straightforward explanation is that .NET raised the CPU baseline requirement between versions, likely moving from v1 to v2 support in .NET 10, which would explain why 2012 hardware suddenly stopped working on the upgrade. The baseline shift to x86-64-v2 in .NET 10 requires specific instruction sets like CMPXCHG16B, LAHF/SAHF, POPCNT, and various SSE variants that older 2012-era processors—particularly some AMD Bulldozer chips and low-power Intel Atoms—don't fully support. Since they mention upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, the baseline requirement likely stayed the same or became stricter, which would explain why their older hardware suddenly stopped working. I'll walk through how to diagnose which baseline instruction set is missing and explore potential workarounds, whether that's upgrading the CPU, using an older .NET version, or adjusting runtime settings if available.","outputTokens":2215,"requestId":"6844:283B0A:10938E2:14E86A5:69FFE2E1"},"id":"3e135f36-9e81-4615-963d-1009ba12c5b8","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:44:48.997Z","parentId":"e37ea8da-31ed-4441-8c88-b381ab16102b"}
